If we put $a_1 = a_2 = \cdots = a_n = 1$ then $f(n) = f(\underbrace{1+1+\cdots+1}_{n}) \le 2nf(1)$. Therefore

$$
\begin{align*} 
(f(a+b))^n &= f((a+b)^n) = f\left(\sum_{i=0}^{n} \binom{n}{i} a^i b^{n-i}\right) \le 2(n+1) \max_{0 \le i \le n} \{f\left(\binom{n}{i} a^i b^{n-i}\right)\} \\ 
&\le 2(n+1) \sum_{i=0}^{n} \binom{n}{i} f(a^i) f(b^{n-i}) \le 4(n+1)f(1) \sum_{i=0}^{n} \binom{n}{i} f(a)^i f(b)^{n-i} \\ 
&= 4(n+1)f(1)(f(a)+f(b))^n \Rightarrow f(a+b) \le \sqrt[n]{4(n+1)f(1)(f(a)+f(b))} 
\end{align*}
$$

If $n$ tends to infinity, we have $\sqrt[n]{4(n+1)f(1)} \to 1$ and this implies the desired result. $\square$

