5. We claim that for every $k \in \mathbb{N}$ and real numbers $a_1, a_2, \dots, a_{2^k}$:

$$
f(a_1 + a_2 + \cdots + a_{2^k}) \le 2^k \max\{f(a_1), f(a_2), \dots, f(a_{2^k})\}
$$

Proof is done by induction on $k$. Basis is obviously the condition (iii). Suppose the claim is true for $k$. For $k+1$ we have:

$$
\begin{align*}
f(a_1 + a_2 + \cdots + a_{2^{k+1}}) &= f((a_1 + a_2 + \cdots + a_{2^k}) + (a_{2^k+1} + \cdots + a_{2^{k+1}})) \\
&\le 2 \max\{f(a_1 + a_2 + \cdots + a_{2^k}) + f(a_{2^k+1} + \cdots + a_{2^{k+1}})\} \\
&\le 2 \max\{2^k \max\{f(a_1), f(a_2), \dots, f(a_{2^k})\}, 2^k \max\{f(a_{2^k+1}), \dots, f(a_{2^{k+1}})\}\} \\
&\le 2^{k+1} \max\{f(a_1), f(a_2), \dots, f(a_{2^{k+1}})\}
\end{align*}
$$

Now suppose that $2^{k-1} < n \le 2^k$:

$$
\begin{align*}
f(a_1 + \cdots + a_n) &= f(a_1 + \cdots + a_n + \underbrace{0 + 0 + \cdots + 0}_{2^k - n}) \\
&\le 2^k \max\{f(a_1), \dots, f(a_n), f(0), \dots, f(0)\} \\
&= 2^k \max\{f(a_1), \dots, f(a_n)\} \le 2n \max\{f(a_1), \dots, f(a_n)\}
\end{align*}
$$

$2^{k-1} < n$ So $2^k < 2n$ and this implies the last inequality.

