3. There is no loss of generality in assuming that $x \ge y \ge z$. We have

$$
\begin{aligned}
x^2 + y^2 + z^2 &= 2(xy + yz + zx) \\
\Rightarrow \quad x^2 + x(-2y - 2z) + y^2 + z^2 - 2yz &= 0 \\
\Rightarrow \quad x = (y + z) \pm \sqrt{(y + z)^2 - y^2 - z^2 + 2yz} = (y + z) \pm 2\sqrt{yz} = (\sqrt{y} \pm \sqrt{z})^2 \\
\Rightarrow \quad \sqrt{x} = \sqrt{y} \pm \sqrt{z}
\end{aligned}
$$
